<br>
When I parse myself again a warrior friend of mine, who is the same level as I, comparably geared and has slightly more AA than I do, they do not outdamage me by any significant margin.  In fact, when you factor in my pet's damage, I am outdamaging them on most mobs, and my &quot;burst&quot; damage is far superior when I decide to decide to burn through all my mana and/or Harm Touch.<br>
<br>
Looking at a few other parsed logs where I'm grouped with warriors, the picture looks about the same.  Against a few I'm actually pretty handily outdamaging them.  The classes traditionally thought of as &quot;DPS classes&quot; (beastlords, magicians, rogues, rangers), from what I'm seeing in my parsing, well deserve to be categorized as such... they have no trouble outdamaging me in typical circumstances (though I can't seem to find any fights where I was grouped with a monk to see how they measure up... but what I recall from some older parses, I wasn't very impressed.)<br>
<br>
I have no problem with grouping with warriors, and by and large I don't think the problem is quite as bad as some argue... I don't think generating aggro is a huge problem for well-equipped warriors (warriors with fast weapons that proc aggro spells, with decent dexterity) who know their business.  I find that with some warriors, I can cast pretty much the same spells I would if I were trying to keep aggro, and the mob never glances at me... though other times, the mobs just insist on attacking me even if I do pull my punches.<br>
<br>
I think the problem is that we knights have spoiled everyone with the ease with which we can typically hold aggro... it doesn't require specific equipment or special skill for us to do it.  A warrior definitely has to put more effort into it, and they do have to rely more on dumb luck.  The problem is, a lot of warriors just don't put the effort into it, and other classes get careless about their aggro due to their experience in grouping with knights.  I think this has given warriors a bad rap and contributes to their perceived lack of value in experience groups.<br>
<br>
I do think the situation is pretty sad and something should probably be done, whether it's totally needed from a balance perspective or not.  It seems that as often as not when I'm grouped with a similar level warrior, I'm the one who's called on to tank.  Typically I prefer to give the warrior a shot, that way I get rid of my spell slots devoted to a taunt spell and put something in with more utility or damage potential, and also, yes, partly out of sympathy.<br>
<br>
Being given a role out of sympathy just sucks.  I remember what it was like to be a class that was sympathy grouped, due to the knight's real and perceived lack of value as compared to classes like monks and warriors (in the pre-PoP era).  Now it appears the tables are turned, and I'll admit that I'm rather tenative in recommending anything that might turn those tables back out of my favor... I don't want to be in that position again.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I think some sort of way for warriors to go into a sustained offensive mode would be a welcome, not harmfully unbalancing change... but I'm far from being an expert.  Possibly they should have some slight to moderate improvements in their ability to hold aggro, along with an even further improvement to their avoidance/mitigation, that would make &quot;chancing&quot; a warrior MT more worthwhile in the eyes of most people.  Again, I'm not an expert.<br>
<br>
That's my two cents.  I could very be wrong on some of this, but I call them like I see them. <p>--Velsor<br>
Shadow Knight of Cazic-Thule<br>
Seeker of the Dark Truth<br>
